{"parse":{"title":"H. F. C. Smith","pageid":3677495,"revid":804561669,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>H. F. C. Smith</b> was a scholar of <a href=\"/wiki/West_Africa\" title=\"West Africa\">West African</a> <a href=\"/wiki/History_of_West_Africa\" title=\"History of West Africa\">history</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/African_culture\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"African culture\">culture</a>.  He was particularly interested in <a href=\"/wiki/Arab\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Arab\">Arab</a> influence in <a href=\"/wiki/Nigeria\" title=\"Nigeria\">Nigeria</a>.\n</p><p>Smith was one of the first historians to document the complex history of conflict between <a href=\"/wiki/Europe\" title=\"Europe\">Europeans</a> and Arabs in Nigeria.<sup class=\"reference plainlinks nourlexpansion\" id=\"ref_Sahara\"><a class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H._F._C._Smith#endnote_Sahara\">[1]</a></sup>  He introduced to the west the existence of massive <a href=\"/wiki/Archive\" title=\"Archive\">archives</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Arabic_literature\" title=\"Arabic literature\">Arabic literature</a> and historical records in Nigeria, which he had anticipated as the natural result of \"a powerful tradition of Arabic learning (which indeed persists to the present day).\" <sup class=\"reference plainlinks nourlexpansion\" id=\"ref_Smith1\"><a class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H._F._C._Smith#endnote_Smith1\">[2]</a></sup>  Smith argued consistently that scholarship had neglected the Arabic history of West Africa, in part because of the complexity of the historical situation and in part because of anxiety over Europe's role.<sup class=\"reference plainlinks nourlexpansion\" id=\"ref_Smith2\"><a class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H._F._C._Smith#endnote_Smith2\">[3]</a></sup>  Smith taught at the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Ibadan\" title=\"University of Ibadan\">University of Ibadan</a>. He was Professor of History at Ahmadu Bello University and ran the Northern History Research Centre. \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=H._F._C._Smith&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ol><li><span class=\"citation wikicite\" id=\"endnote_Sahara\"><b><a href=\"#ref_Sahara\">^</a></b></span> <i>Saharan Studies Newsletter</i> Vol. 9, No. 2 (2003), p.&#160;6 n.3.</li>\n<li><span class=\"citation wikicite\" id=\"endnote_Smith1\"><b><a href=\"#ref_Smith1\">^</a></b></span> Smith, H. F. C. \"Nineteenth-Century Arabic Archives of West Africa\" (The Journal of African History, Vol. 3, No. 2 [1962], 333-336), 334.</li>\n<li><span class=\"citation wikicite\" id=\"endnote_Smith2\"><b><a href=\"#ref_Smith2\">^</a></b></span> Smith, H. F. C. \"A Neglected Theme of West-African History: The Islamic Revolutions of the Nineteenth Century\" (<i>Journal of the Historical Society of Nigeria</i> Vol. 2, No. 1. [1961], 169-185.</li></ol>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Titus_Livius.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Titus_Livius.png/30px-Titus_Livius.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"36\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Titus_Livius.png/45px-Titus_Livius.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/71/Titus_Livius.png/60px-Titus_Livius.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"400\" data-file-height=\"484\" /></a></td><td><i>This article about a historian is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=H._F._C._Smith&amp;action=edit\">expand